x4freetext: Gamma rays were detected with a Harshaw,
NaI(Tl) crystal, three inches in diameter and three
inches long, optically coupled to a Dumont 6363
photomultiplier tube.
Nitrogen gas.
Protons were accelerated with a pressurized,
electrostatic generator. A variable magnetic field
deflected the beam 25 degrees through collimating
apertures, the smallest of which was 0.080 inch x 080
inch in size, into the target chamber. The magnet
current was calibrated against proton energy by
measuring the current at which well-known resonances
in the 19F(p,alpha gamma)150 reaction appeared when
monatomic and diatomic hydrogen ions struck thin,
fluorine targets. In addition, a BF3 counter was used
to locate the known threshold for the 15N(p,n)150
reaction at 3776 kev. The proton energy was known
absolutely to +- one percent over the range of this
experiment. Data were taken with targets of nitrogen
gas prepared from ammonium nitrate. The yield curve
for reaction 15N(p,alpha gamma)12C was measured by
detecting the 4.43-Mev gamma rays resulting from the
fast de-excitation (half-life < 3x10-13 sec) of the
12C nucleus. Since the gamma-ray energy was
independent of the bombarding energy, the detection
efficiency was constant for a given geometry.

x4freetext: The resonance observed in the present paper at
1210 keV has been used to normalize the present work
to the previous absolute measurements. By using the
one-level formula, the new resonances at 3000 keV,
3300 keV, and 3520 keV were extrapolated far enough
away from their resonance positions for their
contributions to the yield to be negligible.
